沃斯利","lifeSummary":"当Richard de Worsley于大约1217年出生在英国英格兰藍卡爾时，他的父亲Geoffrey de Worsley23岁，母亲Agnes de Notton18岁。他于1240年之前与Maud de Wardley在英国结婚。他们至少是3个儿子的父母。他去世于1296年之前。"},"hr":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"oko 1217.–prije 1296.","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277.","1240–1304":"1240.–1304","1240–1296":"1240.–1296","1240–1331":"1240.–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278.","before 1268":"prije 1268.","1296":"1296","1240":"1240.","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"oko 1217.","Bef 1296":"prije 1296.","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278.","1277":"1277.","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"prije 1240.","after 1240":"nakon 1240.","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Francuska","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England"},"cs":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"okolo 1217–před 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"před 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"okolo 1217","Bef 1296":"před 1296","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"před 1240","after 1240":"po 1240","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, Anglie","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Francie","England":"Anglie","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Anglie","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"omkring 1217–før 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"før 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"omkring 1217","Bef 1296":"før 1296","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"før 1240","after 1240":"efter 1240","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"circa 1217–vóór 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"vóór 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"circa 1217","Bef 1296":"vóór 1296","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"vóór 1240","after 1240":"na 1240","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"about 1217–before 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"before 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"about 1217","Bef 1296":"before 1296","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"before 1240","after 1240":"after 1240","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Worsley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Worsley in Lancashire or Worsley Farm in Rock (Worcestershire). The Lancashire placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Weorcgȳth</i> (genitive <i>Weorcgȳthes</i>) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The Worcestershire placename may take its name from a lost stream-name <i>Worf</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Worsley was born about 1217, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffrey de Worsley, was 23 and his mother, Agnes de Notton, was 18. He married Maud de Wardley before 1240, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died before 1296."},"et":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"umbes 1217–enne 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"enne 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","Abt 1217":"umbes 1217","Bef 1296":"enne 1296","1217":"1217","1304":"1304","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","before 1240":"enne 1240","after 1240":"pärast 1240","1219":"1219","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1217–Bef 1296":"noin 1217–ennen vuotta 1296","1217–1296":"1217–1296","1219–1277":"1219–1277","1240–1304":"1240–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1240–1331":"1240–1331","1195–1268":"1195–1268","1200–1278":"1200–1278","before 1268":"ennen vuotta 1268","1296":"1296","1240":"